UML:TaggedValue.value: Main Idea: The main idea of the intended system is to create a comprehensive property management platform that connects property owners (hosts) with potential guests (customers) seeking accommodations. The platform facilitates the entire lifecycle of property rental transactions, from property listing and booking to post-stay actions, ensuring seamless interactions between hosts and guests. Additionally, the system aims to maintain trust and reliability by verifying user identities and property details through platform inspectors.

The web application should function as a platform accessible via web browsers. Users, including Customers (Guests), Property Owners (Hosts), and Platform Inspectors, must be able to access the application's functionalities seamlessly. The web application must be hosted on the same server as the central database. Additionally, it is imperative that the application is compatible with Microsoft Edge, Firefox version 109 and above, and Chrome version 110 and above to ensure optimal performance and user experience.
The web application for book information must maintain a minimum availability of 95%.

UML:ClassifierRole.name: NF4: Concurrent Users and Response Time

UML:TaggedValue.value: The application must be capable of handling up to 500 users accessing the platform simultaneously.

Tha application should be capable of managing data for the listed accommodations and users. This includes information for properties listed by Property Owner(Hosts), details of customers (Guests) making booking, and records of Platform Inspectors verifying property accuracy and user identities. Specifically, the system must accommodate details for up to 1,000 properties and their respective bookings, as well as records for 1000 users and their interactions with the platform, including bookings and inspections.

The application must perform daily backups of user and booking data, including information on customer(Guests), Property Owner(Hosts), and Platform Inspectors. This backup process should be completed within a maximum of 10 minutes and should occur automatically during nighttime hours.
The system will be localized in Czech and English. Only English will be delivered with application
The system must be realized in the platform color theme of white and black.

Responsible for verifying user identities and the properties listed on the platform. They meticulously validate the authenticity of user-provided information, including personal details and documentation, to maintain a secure and trustworthy user base. Additionally, platform inspectors verify property details to uphold the credibility and reliability of the platform for both users and stakeholders.

Represents property owners who list their properties on the platform. Hosts fulfill responsibilities such as creating and verifying property listings, managing booking requests, reviewing guest feedback, and handling post-stay actions such as charges or refunds. They play a crucial role in maintaining property listings and ensuring a seamless experience for guests.

An authenticated user is an individual or entity who has successfully proven their identity to a system or application through a specified authentication process. This process typically involves providing some form of credentials, such as a username and password, or other means, to verify their identity.

Tasked with maintaining the cleanliness and presentation of properties listed on the platform. They receive notifications and perform cleaning tasks promptly after guests check out, ensuring that properties are well-prepared for incoming guests. Cleaning personnel play a crucial role in enhancing guest satisfaction and maintaining the overall quality of listed properties

Refers to authenticated users who utilize the web application to browse and search for properties, make reservations, provide feedback on their stay experiences, and handle post-stay payments. Customers engage in various activities within the platform, contributing to the booking and feedback processes.
UC11: Browsing and Searching for Properties

Represents individuals interacting with the system, representing both visitors exploring the system without authentication and users who have logged in. Users can access public information, and perform other non-authenticated actions.
This use case enables authenticated users to access and review their booking history on the platform, allowing them to track past reservations and upcoming stays.

UML:ClassifierRole.name: Hospitality Property Managemnet IS - Customer Module

UML:TaggedValue.value: In this use case, customers initiate and confirm reservations for selected properties. They specify booking details such as desired dates, the number of guests, and any special requests. Once the reservation is made, customers receive confirmation and booking details.
During their stay, customers check in to their reserved accommodations, and have the opportunity to provide feedback on various aspects such as cleanliness, amenities, and service quality.

After their stay, customers settle any outstanding payments or additional charges incurred during their visit. This may include charges for additional services availed during the stay or adjustments to the initial reservation costs. Payments are processed post-stay to ensure accuracy and transparency in billing.

UML:UseCase.name: UC11: Browsing and Searching for Properties

UML:TaggedValue.value: Customers searching for suitable accommodations according to their preferences and requirements. They utilize search functionalities to explore available listings, apply filters, and find properties that align with their needs.
UC11: Browsing and Searching for Properties

Customers handle payments related to their reservations, which may include upfront deposits or full payments. Payment methods are securely processed through the platform, providing convenience and security for guests.

In this use case, the host handle reservation requests from guests. They have the authority to accept or decline booking requests based on availability, suitability, or other factors. Additionally, property owners prepare their properties for guest arrivals, ensuring that accommodations are clean, well-maintained, and equipped with necessary amenities.

After guests' stays, property owners may need to handle post-stay actions, such as charging for additional services or damages incurred during the guest's visit. Property owners review charges, if necessary, and ensure that any post-stay transactions are accurately processed and communicated to the guests.

This use case enables hosts to create and verify property listings on the platform. Hosts provide detailed information about the property, including descriptions, amenities, photos, pricing, and availability. It ensures that property listings accurately represent the properties to attract potential guests.

UML:ClassifierRole.name: Hospitality Property Management IS - Host Module
Hospitality Property Management IS - Maintenance Module

UML:TaggedValue.value: It focuses on facilitating communication between cleaning personnel and host. Cleaning personnel may need to report any issues or concerns encountered during the cleaning process.
After guests check out, the system assigns cleaning personnel to tasks within a limited time frame. This ensures efficient turnaround between guest stays and maintains cleanliness standards.

Users can view detailed information about a specific property by selecting it from the list. Property details include comprehensive information about the property, such as photos, descriptions, amenities, pricing, availability, and any additional features or policies.

Users of the platform can access a list of properties. The list provides basic information about each property, such as the property name, location, and brief description, allowing users to browse available options.

Users can access the profile of the host or property owner associated with a particular property. The host profile provides information about the property owner, including their name, contact information, profile picture, and any additional details or credentials they choose to share. This allows users to learn more about the host and establish trust before making a reservation.

Allows users to browse the web application and view available properties without the need for authentication. Users can explore various listings, search for properties, and access general information about the platform's services and features.
Once authenticated, users have the option to log out of the system, thereby lost access to any functions associated with their role.
Enables users to create a new account on the platform, granting them access to additional functionalities such as booking properties or leaving reviews.

In order to access the system, users are required to input their email address and password, which must correspond to the stored credentials. If the provided information does not match, users are notified, without disclosing whether the email is registered or indicating which credential (email or password) was incorrect.

This use case involves the verification of the identities of new hosts and customers joining the platform. Platform inspectors are responsible for validating the authenticity of user-provided information, such as personal details and documentation, to maintain a secure and trustworthy user base.

Platform inspectors are tasked with confirming the existence and accuracy of properties listed on the platform. This process involves conducting thorough inspections or audits to ensure that the properties meet the platform's standards and accurately reflect their descriptions. By verifying property details, platform inspectors help uphold the credibility and reliability of the platform for both users and stakeholders.

Platform inspectors investigate and resolve reports submitted by users regarding suspicious activities, violations of platform policies, or discrepancies in property listings. This may involve gathering additional information and taking appropriate actions to address the reported issues, such as issuing warnings, suspending accounts, or removing listings.

This use case encompasses the information provided by users seeking authentication. This data includes both personal information, such as identification details, as well as property-related data, including listings, descriptions, and associated details.

The goal of the system is to provide a user-friendly and efficient platform for property owners to list their properties and for customers to find and book accommodations that meet their needs. The system aims to streamline the booking process, enhance communication between hosts and guests, and maintain the quality and reliability of listed properties. Ultimately, the system strives to optimize the user experience for both hosts and guests while fostering trust and satisfaction.

The problem domain revolves around the challenges associated with property management and rental transactions in the hospitality industry. Property owners often face difficulties in effectively marketing their properties and managing reservations, while potential guests encounter hurdles in finding suitable accommodations and ensuring a seamless booking experience. Moreover, ensuring the authenticity and reliability of user identities and property listings presents significant concerns for both hosts and guests. Addressing these challenges requires a robust and efficient property management platform that streamlines processes, enhances communication, and maintains trust and credibility.

The main idea of the intended system is to create a comprehensive property management platform that connects hosts with potential guests (customers) seeking accommodations. The platform facilitates the entire lifecycle of property rental transactions, from property listing and booking to post-stay actions, ensuring seamless interactions between hosts and guests. Additionally, the system aims to maintain trust and reliability by verifying user identities and property details through platform inspectors.

The agenda of the system includes:
1. Creating a user-friendly platform for property owners to list their properties, providing comprehensive details and images to attract potential guests. 2. Facilitating seamless booking processes for customers, allowing them to search for properties, view details, make reservations, and handle payments securely. 3. Implementing verification mechanisms for user identities and property details, ensuring authenticity and reliability on the platform. 4. Enabling effective communication between hosts and guests throughout the booking process and post-stay interactions. 5. Managing post-stay actions such as additional charges, refunds, and feedback collection to ensure a satisfactory experience for both hosts and guests. 6. Providing transparency and accountability through features such as booking history access and report investigation for suspicious activities. 7. Maintaining the overall quality and credibility of the platform through continuous monitoring, verification, and resolution of reported issues.

EAScenario.name: No Booking History
EAScenario.description: If the authenticated user has no booking history (either past or upcoming): The system displays a message indicating that there are no bookings to show.
EAScenario.subject: EAID_F0B0F8D6_CEBF_4b2e_9D92_DDFFA87F0230

EAScenario.name: View Booking History
EAScenario.description:
1. The authenticated user navigates to the booking history section within their account settings.
  2. The system fetches the booking records associated with the their account from the database.
  3. The system presents the authenticated user with a list of their past bookings and upcoming reservations.
  4. The authenticated user selects a specific booking from the list to view its details.
  5. Detailed information about the selected booking, including dates, property details, guest/host information, and any additional notes, is displayed.
EAScenario.subject: EAID_F0B0F8D6_CEBF_4b2e_9D92_DDFFA87F0230

EAScenario.name: Create Reservation
EAScenario.description:
The scenario describes the process of creating the reservation.
  1. Customer selects a property and initiates the reservation process.
  2. Customer provides booking details including dates, number of guests, and any special requests.
  3. System confirms availability and calculates booking cost.
  4. Customer confirms the reservation and makes payment if required.
  5. System generates booking confirmation and sends it to the customer.
EAScenario.subject: EAID_42892DFD_6B27_4ced_A035_17D2D4AA38A2

EAScenario.name: Payment Failure
EAScenario.description:
This scenario describes the situation when the payment is not approved.
  1. Customer attempts to make a payment.
  2. Payment processing fails due to insufficient funds.
  3. System notifies the customer of the payment failure and provides alternative payment options.
EAScenario.subject: EAID_42892DFD_6B27_4ced_A035_17D2D4AA38A2

EAScenario.name: Browsing and Searching for Properties
EAScenario.description:
The scenario describe the process of browsing and searching for properties.
  1. The customer accesses the property search interface and use the action to see the list of properties.
  1. <include> Show list of properties
  2. The customer uses action to enters search criteria such as location.
  3. The system retrieves relevant property listings matching the search criteria.
  4. The customer browses through the listings, reviews property details, and applies filters as needed.
  5. The customer selects a property of interest for further consideration.
EAScenario.subject: EAID_9007FA99_56A7_40a0_82FD_DC00A07A79A4

EAScenario.name: No result found
EAScenario.description:
This scenario describes the situation when the search criteria of a customer is not found.
  1. Customer enters search criteria.
  2. System does not find any properties matching the specified criteria.
  3. System notifies the customer of no results found and suggests refining search criteria.
EAScenario.subject: EAID_9007FA99_56A7_40a0_82FD_DC00A07A79A4

EAScenario.name: Discrepancies in Listing
EAScenario.description:
This scenario pertains to instances where discrepancies exist within the listings.
  1. Inspector detects discrepancies in the property listing.
  2. Inspector contacts the property owner for clarification.
  3. Property owner provides additional information or makes necessary corrections.
  4. Inspector re-evaluates the property listing and proceeds with verification.
EAScenario.subject: EAID_D748CC5D_F07C_4133_9C91_8E9D0F19F173

EAScenario.name: Listing a Property
EAScenario.description:
This scenario describe the use case where the use case wherein a host seeks to list a property within the system.
  1. Host initiates the process of listing a property.
  2. Host accesses the property listing section on the platform.
  3. Host provides comprehensive details about the property, including descriptions, amenities, photos, pricing, and availability.
  4. Host submits the property listing for verification.
  5. The platform inspector reviews the property listing and associated details.
  6. If the property meets platform standards, the inspector approves the listing, and the system notifies users of the property's verification status.If the property does not meet platform standards, the inspector rejects the listing, and the system notifies users of the rejection.
EAScenario.subject: EAID_D748CC5D_F07C_4133_9C91_8E9D0F19F173

EAScenario.name: Basic Path
EAScenario.description:
1. User accesses the property listings section of the platform.
  2. User utilizes search filters or enters specific criteria to refine the property list.
  3. System retrieves a list of available properties from the database based on the user's search criteria.
  4. The list is displayed to the user, showing basic information about each property, such as name, location, and brief description.
  5. User selects a property from the list to view its details.
EAScenario.subject: EAID_757EB483_DE4F_4009_9FAE_EA4126C3A3E6

EAScenario.name: Insufficient Documentation
EAScenario.description:
1. Inspector reviews the provided user information.
  2. Inspector determines that the documentation provided is insufficient.
  3. Inspector requests additional documentation from the user.
  4. User provides additional documentation.
  5. Inspector re-evaluates the provided information and proceeds with verification.
EAScenario.subject: EAID_161201E1_25DA_4c4c_829E_C63F79DFE649

EAScenario.name: User Verification
EAScenario.description:
This scenario describes the process of verifying users identity.
  1. Platform inspector accesses the user verification section.
  2. Inspector reviews the provided user information and documentation.
  3. Inspector verifies the authenticity of the information against specified criteria.
  4. If verification is successful, the inspector approves the user's identity, and the system notifies the user of successful verification. If verification fails, the inspector rejects the user's identity, and the system notifies the user of the rejection.
EAScenario.subject: EAID_161201E1_25DA_4c4c_829E_C63F79DFE649

EAScenario.description:
1. Inspector detects discrepancies in the property listing.
  2. Inspector contacts the property owner for clarification.
  3. Property owner provides additional information or makes necessary corrections.
  4. Inspector re-evaluates the property listing and proceeds with verification.
EAScenario.subject: EAID_2341188E_0E3F_4418_8D84_FCDEE5D7F045

EAScenario.name: Property Verification
EAScenario.description:
1. Platform inspector accesses the property verification section.
  2. Inspector reviews the property listing and associated details.
  3. Inspector conducts an inspection or audit of the property.
  4. If the property meets platform standards, Inspector approves the property listing. And the system notifies users of the property's verification status.
  5. If the property does not meet platform standards, Inspector rejects the property listing. And the system notifies users of the rejection.
EAScenario.subject: EAID_2341188E_0E3F_4418_8D84_FCDEE5D7F045

EAScenario.name: Insufficient Evidence
EAScenario.description:
1. Inspector investigates the reported issue but finds insufficient evidence.
  2. Inspector contacts the reporting user for more information.
  3. If additional evidence is provided, The inspector re-evaluates the reported issue based on the new information. If insufficient evidence persists, the inspector closes the report without taking further action.
EAScenario.subject: EAID_79D41580_A888_4b5d_95F1_8087DD156119

EAScenario.name: Report Investigation
EAScenario.description:
1. Inspector accesses the report investigation section.
  2. Inspector reviews the reported issue and associated details.
  3. Inspector gathers additional information or conducts audits as necessary.
  4. Inspector takes appropriate actions based on investigation findings.
  5. If violations are confirmed: Inspector issues warnings, suspends accounts, or removes listings as appropriate. If no violations are found: Inspector closes the report without taking further action.
EAScenario.subject: EAID_79D41580_A888_4b5d_95F1_8087DD156119
